@node "introduction" "Introduction"
ANetGUI allows browsing the Aminet @{b}off-line@{ub} (without having to connect to Internet). It is a great advantage for modem owners or for people without Internet access on Amiga.

This program uses@{" MUI 3.1 " link "MUI"}'s new @{b}Drag-N-Drop@{ub} possibility. Thanks to it it's simple to use.

@{b}ANetGUI/II@{ub} allows@{" searching for files " link "find_window"}fulfilling the criteria. It's a very useful function as you can find files without having to connect to Internet.

I really wanted ANetGUI to be able to generate FTP scripts, but unfortunately I haven't found anyone, who could write them.
@endnode

@node "requirements" "Requirements"
ANetGUI/II requires:

· Workbench 2.0 (V36)
· Kickstart 2.04 (V37)
· @{" MUI3.1 " link "MUI"}
· @{" INDEX file " link "indexfile"}

If you own the above, you can run ANetGUI.

A couple of things won't hurt:
· Workbench & Kickstart 3.0 (V39)
· registered version of MUI (looks nicer)
· internet access on Amiga and MountFTP
· fast processor and harddrive
· ARexx running (for ARexx scripts)

If you own the above, ANetGUI will run like a dream.
@endnode

@node "main_window" "ANetGUI - main window"
ANetGUI's main window consists of the following things:
· @{" directories list " link "lst_dirs"}
· @{" files list " link "lst_files"}
· @{" selected files list " link "lst_selected"}
· @{" control buttons " link "buttons"}

If you use ANetGUI for the first time, go to@{" list options " link "list_window"}, select the@{" INDEX file " link "indexfile"}and click on Add to list. This convertion may take a couple of minutes, depending on INDEX and CPU. When the program ends the@{" convertion " link "index_to_dirs"}, the list of dirs should appear@{" on the left side of the main window" link "lst_dirs"}.
@endnode

@node "indexfile" "INDEX files"
Aminet INDEX files are files with list of all files on Aminet or on one Aminet CD.

  @{b}List of all files on Aminet@{ub}
If you have a fast Internet access, I suggest you download it from one of the Aminet servers (ie. @{u}http://www.aminet.org/~aminet/INDEX@{uu} or @{u}INDEX.Z@{uu} - GNU ZIP compressed INDEX).
If you don't, then you can always copy it from Aminet CD (ie. @{b}AMINET20:Aminet/AMINET@{ub} - AMINET, not INDEX).

  @{b}List of files on one Aminet CD@{ub}
On every Aminet CD there's an INDEX of files on that particular CD-ROM. This file's name is INDEX (ie. @{b}AMINET19:Aminet/INDEX).

  @{b}List of recently uploaded files@{ub} @{i}(RECENT) @{ui}
On Aminet there's a list of newest files, it's called @{b}RECENT@{ub} (or @{b}RECENT.Z@{ub} - GNU ZIP). You can also subscribe to receive it automatically via e-mail. More info available on Aminet WWW sites. If you reveice @{b}RECENT@{ub} list via e-mail, just copy the list with the header to any file.

Since updating from INDEX every week is unreal for most, it's possible to update by @{b}RECENT@{ub} files. You have to select the RECENT file (or the file with the text from e-mail) and add it to the list. However newer versions of files mostly replace older files (AStart21.lha replaced AStart20.lha), that's why it's adviced to update the list entirely from time to time (ie. every 2 months).
@endnode

@node "index_to_dirs" "Converting INDEX files"
INDEX files have one disadvantage, which makes work on them very hard - all the directories are in one file. That's why ANetGUI works on single directories list files.

Most advantages of such storing of files are:
· ability to add files to the list
· faster reading of dirs list
· faster reading of files list
· saving up space on disk (ANetGUI dirs take up less space than INDEX files)
@endnode

@node "lst_dirs" "ANetGUI - list of directories"
It is a list of directories on Aminet. Doubleclick on a dir to see it's contents.

If there are no entries in this list, look@{" here " link "main_window"}.
@endnode
@node "lst_files" "ANetGUI - list of files"
It is a list of all available files in selected directory. In order to this list not being empty, you have to select a@{" dir " link "lst_dirs"}.

If this list isn't empty, to add entry(ies) to selected files list you can do one of the following things:
· doubleclick on an entry
· select one or more entries and drag it to the selected files list
· select one or more entries and klick on the "Add to list" button

WARNING! Readme viewing option added in version 4.11 makes doubleclicking on description show the .readme file, not adding it to the list.
@endnode

@node "lst_selected" "ANetGUI - selected files list"
It is a list of selected files from Aminet.

To remove entry(ies) from list, you can:
· doubleclick on one entry
· select one or more entries and click on "Remove From List" button

@{" In order to add to list " link "lst_files"}

You can sort the entries by dragging them.

WARNING! Readme viewing option added in version 4.11 makes doubleclicking on description show the .readme file, not removing it from the list.
@endnode

@node "buttons" "ANetGUI - buttons"
The buttons and the functions:
@{b}Find@{ub} - @{" looks " link "find_window"}for files matching the criteria
@{b}List options@{ub} -  @{" managing the files list " link "list_window"}
@{b}Add to list@{ub} - adds selected entry(ies) to selected files list
@{b}Remove from list@{ub} - removes selected entry(ies) from selected files list
@{b}New@{ub} - removes all the files from the selected files list
@{b}Load@{ub} - load the files into selected files list (clears the list first)
@{b}Save@{ub} - saves the selected files list
@{b}Save as...@{ub} - saves selected files list as
@{b}Append@{ub} - load the files into selected files list (does not clear the list first)
@{b}Launch script@{ub} - launches an ARexx script
@{b}Quit@{ub} - exits ANetGUI
@{b}About@{ub} - information about the program, version
@endnode

@node "find_window" "ANetGUI - finding files"
Finding window consists of four items:
· @{" patterns for name, dir and description " link "find_pattern"}
· convertion gauge
· search, clear the list and remove entries buttons
· mode selection radio
· found files list

Patterns are the criteria for searching. They are divided into 3 criteria. For more info on pattern creating,@{" click here " link "find_pattern"}.

Convertion gauge shows currently converted directory.

"Find files" button starts searching.
@{b}WARNING!@{ub} You cannot break the searching process, so think before searching.

The "Clear list" button clears the found files list.
The "Remove selected" button removes currently selected files in found files list.

Mode selection radio is used to choose from one of the following search modes:
· @{b}dir @{i}and @{ui}(file @{i}or @{ui}desc)@{ub}
· @{b}dir @{i}and @{ui}(file @{i}and @{ui}desc)@{ub}

Found files list is very similar to@{" files list " link "lst_files"}.

When the list isn't empty, you can add entry(ies) to selected list by doing one of the following:
· doubleclicking on an entry
· select one or more entries and dragging them to the selected list

To remove an entry, select it (multiselecting is possible) and click on "Remove selected" button.

WARNING! Readme viewing option added in version 4.11 makes doubleclicking on description show the .readme file, not adding it to the list.
@endnode

@node "find_pattern" "ANetGUI - finding patterns"
Finding pattern sets the criteria for accepting a field.

There are two types of pattern
· @{b}AmigaDOS pattern@{ub} (ie. "#?.lha") - ANetGUI/II uses @{i}ParsePatternNoCase() @{ui}to match this type of pattern. It's very useful if you want to enter name pattern, because it allows very complex patterns. Here are some of the symbols
@{b}#@{ub} - searches for number of the same patterns (ie. @{b}#A@{ub} will be true for @{b}A@{ub}, @{b}AA@{ub}, @{b}AaAaa@{ub} but will not be true for @{b}AbA@{ub})
@{b}?@{ub} - replaces any character (ie. @{b}AStart2?.lha@{ub} will be true for @{b}AStart20.lha@{ub}, but will not be true for @{b}AStart12.lha@{ub}, @{b}#?x.lha@{ub} will be true for every name ending with @{b}x.lha@{ub} - @{b}cxx.lha@{ub} will be true, @{b}thanx.lha@{ub} as well, however @{b}thanks.lha@{ub} will not)
@{b}(xx|yy)@{ub} - normal commas, this example will be true for @{b}xx@{ub} or @{b}yy@{ub} (allows any number of "@{b}|@{ub}", other special symbols and commas in commas (also character commas) - ie. @{b}(music#?.lha|#?text#?.lha|wkUtils.lha)@{ub} and @{b}(music#?|#?text#?|wkUtils).lha@{ub} are exactly the same)
@{b}[]@{ub} - character commas, compare just one character, are true, if this char is one of the chars in commas (ie. @{b}#?.[ace]@{ub} is true for files with extenstion @{b}.a@{ub}, @{b}.c@{ub} or @{b}.e@{ub})
@{b}a-e@{ub} - used @{b}only@{ub} in character commas, is replaced with char from "@{b}a@{ub}" to "@{b}e@{ub}" (@{b}abcde@{ub}), @{b}w-z@{ub} replaces "@{b}wxyz@{ub}".
@{b}~@{ub} - negation, expression negated has to be in commas - ie. @{b}~([a-y]#?.lha)@{ub} will be true for files beginning with z or numbers

· @{b}many words pattern@{ub} is simplier than the previous one, it's based on many words separated by spaces. If we want the word to consist space (like name and surname - "Wojciech Kocjan"), it should be put in commas.

If you will use @{b}#@{ub}, @{b}?@{ub}, @{b}~@{ub} or @{b}|@{ub} in a pattern it will be treated as an AmigaDOS pattern. Otherwise it will be treated as many words pattern.
@endnode

@node "list_window" "ANetGUI - list managing"
You have to be familiar with this window from the first time. This window is used to operate the entire list, allows adding, refreshing and removing the list.

@{b}Aminet related options@{ub} are options directly or indirectly related with AMINET.

@{b}Add to list@{ub} is used to add new entries into the list. First you should select the@{" INDEX file " link "indexfile"}

@{b}Rescan list@{ub} refreshes the directories list. It can happen that the dirs list is not right. Then click on this button and the program will update it.

@{b}Clear list@{ub} - @{b}removes@{ub} everything from the directories list. I suggest you really consider using this option. Useful if you want to add a completely new@{" INDEX " link "indexfile"}.

@{b}The gauge below @{ub}- works only if there is an@{" INDEX file " link "indexfile"}added. Shows the percentage done.

@{b}Clean up the list@{ub} removes the files that have newer versions in the list. This process can take some time and should be done after every adding (not the first adding) into the list.

@{b}Pattern of dirs not to clean up@{ub} - some dirs take some time to clean up, but the files there do not usualy have newer versions (like in @{b}mods/@{ub} and @{b}pix/@{ub}). You can enter the pattern for the dirs that do not have to be cleaned up.

@{b}Available lists of files@{ub} (radio buttons on the right) are used to choose the list. It's very useful if you want to have INDEX of entire Aminet and one AminetCD. This option is new for @{b}ANetGUI/II v3@{ub}. There can be up to 22 lists of files. There's a separate program to edit those entries, called@{" SetupANetGUI " link "SetupANetGUI"}.
@endnode

